Introduction¶

Ecommerce website analysis and A/B testing project. The new site was tested. The objectives of the project are:¶

  • Evaluate the main indicators of conversion and income of the current and new version of the website;
  • Compare site versions with each other. Is the new site for commerce better or not?
  • Dive into additional metrics and assess their impact on conversions.

1.1 Description of the dataset¶

Below is the description of the data, there are a total of 7 columns and 287556 rows:

Data columns Purpose Valid values
user_id Unique ID Int64 values
timestamp Time stamp when the user visited the webpage object
group The division into groups depending on which page the user went to: the old or the new web page.
However, some inaccurate rows are present in the initial data, such as a control group user is matched with a new' page.		 ['control', 'variant']
site It denotes whether the user visited the old or new webpage. ['old', 'new']
converted It denotes whether the user decided to pay for the company's product. Here, 1 means yes, the user bought the product. [0, 1]
country It indicates which country the user is from. Here US USA, CA Canada, UK United Kingdom. [US, CA, UK]
revenue Amount of income, in $. [float64]

Part II - A/B Test¶

An A/B test compares data samples to determine if there is a difference between them.
We are testing the old and new webpages. In this section, we will conduct tests on the parameters *Converted* and *Revenue*.

Contents:¶

  • 2.1 Define Control Group & Test Group
  • 2.2 Outliers

converted Conversion Rate:

  • 2.3.1 Bootstrap
  • 2.3.2 Binomial test
  • 2.4.Z-test

revenue Conversion Income:

  • 2.3.3 Bootstrap
  • 2.5 Shapiro Test
  • 2.6.Mann-Whitney Test:

The base assumption is that the new page is no better than the old page, unless we can prove with 95% certainty that the new page is definitely better. Except that we can make Type 1 errors with an "α" factor of 0.05 or 5%.
This will be our null hypothesis and the alternative hypothesis (**$H_0$** and **$H_1$**) as follows:
¶

  1. The Null Hypotheses: P_new - P_old <= 0: $$H_0: P_{new} - P_{old} \leq 0 $$

  2. The Alternative Hypotheses: P_new - P_old > 0: $$H_1: P_{new} - P_{old} > 0 $$

2.3 Bootstrap¶

1 To bootstrap the sample

2 Then simulate normal distributation under the null hypothesis with the center of the simulation closest to the alternative ( in our case zero) and standard deviation equal to sampling distribution ( in our case bootstraping sample standard deviation)

3 Then we visualize the distributions

By this method, we compare in two parameters:¶

  • Conversion rate
  • Revenue

Let us now simulate and bootstraping each of the control group and the variant group using the random generation method numpy.random.choice(), and then make a sampling distribution for $(p{'}_{new}$ - $p{'}_{old})$ with a number of repetitions of 10,000 times using the iterative for loop.

In [42]:
# Sampling distribution 
p_diffs_con = []

for i in tqdm(range(1000)):
    sample_new_page = np.random.choice([1, 0], size=n_new, p=[p_new_con, 1-p_new_con], replace= True)
    sample_old_page = np.random.choice([1, 0], size=n_old, p=[p_old_con, 1-p_old_con], replace= True)
    p_diffs_con.append(sample_new_page.mean() - sample_old_page.mean())

p_diffs_con = np.array(p_diffs_con) # convert to numpy array

100%|██████████████████████████████████████████████████████████████████████████████| 1000/1000 [00:11<00:00, 87.41it/s]
In [43]:
#Looking at the sampling distribution as a normal distribution under the null hypothesis through the histogram
null_vals_con= np.random.normal(0, p_diffs_con.std(), p_diffs_con.size)

low, high = np.percentile(null_vals_con, 2.5), np.percentile(null_vals_con, 97.5)
low2, high2 = np.percentile(p_diffs_con, 2.5), np.percentile(p_diffs_con, 97.5)
plt.figure(figsize=(8,5))

green = plt.hist(null_vals_con, color='#0ca663AA', label='Normal Distribution under the null hypothesis')

2.4 Z-test: Conversion Rate.¶

In the bootstrap section, we built a p_diffs representing the difference in the "converted" probability $(p{'}_{new}-p{'}_{old})$ for your two simulated samples 10,000 times.
Another way for comparing the mean of two independent and normal distribution is a **two-sample z-test**. You can perform the Z-test to calculate the Z_score and p_value.

Now use sm.stats.proportions_ztest() to compute your test statistic and p-value. Here is a helpful link on using the built in.

The syntax is:

proportions_ztest(count_array, nobs_array, alternative='larger')

where,

  • count_array = represents the number of "converted" for each group
  • nobs_array = represents the total number of observations (rows) in each group
  • alternative = choose one of the values from [‘two-sided’, ‘smaller’, ‘larger’] depending upon two-tailed, left-tailed, or right-tailed respectively.

    Hint:
    It's a two-tailed if you defined $H_1$ as $(p_{new} = p_{old})$.
    It's a left-tailed if you defined $H_1$ as $(p_{new} < p_{old})$.
    It's a right-tailed if you defined $H_1$ as $(p_{new} > p_{old})$.

In [56]:
# number of conversions with the new_page
convert_new = variant_converted.sum()
# number of conversions with the old_page
convert_old = control_converted.sum()
print(f'Number of "converted" for each group >>> convert_old: {convert_old}, convert_new: {convert_new}')
print(f'Total number of observations (rows) in each group >>> n_old: {n_old}, n_new: {n_new}')

Number of "converted" for each group >>> convert_old: 17091, convert_new: 16862
Total number of observations (rows) in each group >>> n_old: 141855, n_new: 141890
In [57]:
# import statsmodels.api as sm
z_score, p_value = sm.stats.proportions_ztest([convert_new, convert_old], [n_new, n_old],alternative='larger')
print(z_score, p_value)

-1.3487832789439451 0.9112967064842583

Z_score means the amount of standard deviation of our value from the mean. Therefore, in our case, the observed difference in the sample is -1.35 standard deviations to the left of the center of zero.


Z-test is performed when the sample size is large, and the population variance is known. The z-score represents the distance between the two "converted" success rates in terms of the standard error.

Next step is to make a decision to reject or fail to reject the null hypothesis based on comparing these two values:

  • $Z_{score}$
  • $Z_{\alpha}$ or $Z_{0.05}$, also known as critical value at 95% confidence interval. $Z_{0.05}$ is 1.645 for one-tailed tests, and 1.960 for two-tailed test. You can determine the $Z_{\alpha}$ from the z-table manually.

Decide if your hypothesis is either a two-tailed, left-tailed, or right-tailed test. Accordingly, reject OR fail to reject the null based on the comparison between $Z_{score}$ and $Z_{\alpha}$. We determine whether or not the $Z_{score}$ lies in the "rejection region" in the distribution. In other words, a "rejection region" is an interval where the null hypothesis is rejected iff the $Z_{score}$ lies in that region.

Hint: For a right-tailed test, reject null if $Z_{score}$ > $Z_{\alpha}$. For a left-tailed test, reject null if $Z_{score}$ < $Z_{\alpha}$.

Now we need to extract the value of $Z_{\alpha}$, which is "α" by 0.05 but after converting it to a standardized value, through the scipy library as follows:

In [58]:
# from scipy import stats

Za= stats.norm.ppf(1-0.05)
Za
Out[58]:
1.6448536269514722

Our test is based on the right tailed.

The comparison between $Z_{score}$ and $Z_{\alpha}$ is made based on the following:

  • For a right-tailed test, reject null hypothesis if $Z_{score}$ > $Z_{\alpha}$.
  • For a left-tailed test, reject null hypothesis if $Z_{score}$ < $Z_{\alpha}$.

Now let's compare the two values using the following graph:

In [59]:

plt.ylabel("frequency of occurence", labelpad=14);

From the graph, we find that the line for the $Z_{score}$ region is not within the shaded region of $Z_{\alpha}$ which is the rejection region, and it is far from it.

P_value = 0.91 > 0.05. The results are consistent with previous conversion rate findings. We cannot reject (𝐻0).

2.5 Check Normality: Shapiro Test¶

Procedure for successful testing:

  • Using the Shapiro-Wilk test to check if each group was drawn from a normal distribution.

  • If Normal distribution, Using Levene's test to check if k samples have equal variances (Homogeneity of variances).

  • If Normal & homogeneity, apply T-test.

  • If Normal but non-homogeneity, apply Welch Test

  • If Non-Normal, apply Mann Whitney U Test.

We have previously concluded that the distribution is not normal.
Nevertheless, let's check the `revenue` distribution with a test.

In [64]:
# Visual Shapiro Test
import math

dict_sample = [variant, control, variant_rev, control_rev]
title_sample = ['variant', 'control', 'variant_rev', 'control_rev']
cols = 2
rows = math.ceil(len(dict_sample) / cols)

fig, axes = plt.subplots(rows, cols, figsize=(20, 14), dpi=50)
plt.subplots_adjust(wspace=0.2, hspace=0.5)

l = 0
for i in range(rows):
    for j in range(cols):
        if len(dict_sample) == l:
            break
        else:
            sample = dict_sample[l] 
            axes = fig.add_subplot(rows,cols,(l+1))
            stats.probplot(sample, dist="norm", plot=pylab)
            axes.get_yaxis().set_visible(False)
            axes.get_xaxis().set_visible(False)
            pv = shapiro(sample)
            if pv.pvalue > 0.05:
                plt.title(f"{title_sample[l]}\nP_value = {pv.pvalue}. \nIt's normal distribution\n", fontsize=16)
            else:
                plt.title(f"{title_sample[l]}\nP_value = {pv.pvalue}. \nIt's not normal distribution\n", fontsize=16)
            l += 1;

The distribution is not normal in any of the samples.

2.6 Mann-Whitney Parametric Test: REVENUE. Check the equality of average income¶

Let's check the value of the statistics of the Mann-Whitney test. Some sources have a limitation of applicability in case of duplicate data. There are a lot of zero values, so in this case we need to be careful about this criterion.

Variants: Our sample groups

In [65]:
def ab_test(variant, control): 
    alpha = 0.05 
    mannwhitney = mannwhitneyu(variant, control) #or alternative='greater'
    if mannwhitney.pvalue < alpha:  
        print(f"\nP_value = {mannwhitney.pvalue:.8f} \n\nGroups is different. Reject the hypothesis of equality of average income.")
    else: 
        print(f"\nP_value = {mannwhitney.pvalue:.8f}. \n\nGroups is similar. Accept the hypothesis of equality of average income.")

The results obtained from the A/B test above can be achieved by performing a regression. A machine learning technique, like regression, takes a more personalized approach to inference by seeking to predict the outcome of each point in a given set of data.
Unlike previous tests, where the hypothesis was checked more > (or <) than the studied values, Logistic regression depends on the hypothesis about the occurrence of the event or not, in other words, it is equal or not equal to:

$$H_0: P_{new} - P_{old} = 0 $$ $$H_1: P_{new} - P_{old}\neq 0 $$

  • The variable conversion it has two values 0 or 1, it can be considered as a binary categorical variable.
  • Other variables group/site and country can also be converted to binary values.
  • Moreover, timestamp can also be split into, for example, morning, afternoon, evening, and converted to binary values.

To predict categorical features, we will use Logistic Regression.

When choosing independent variables for analysis, look for variables that describe different aspects of the phenomenon being modeled and avoid variables that contain the same information. How to know if two or more variables are redundant?

Let's define a Variance Increasing Factor (VIF) variance_inflation_factor for each feature. The VIF value is a measure of variable redundancy that helps you decide which variables can be removed from the model without compromising the strength of the model.

In [89]:
# from patsy import dmatrices
# from statsmodels.stats.outliers_influence import variance_inflation_factor

y, x = dmatrices("converted ~ ab_page + UK + US + ab_page&UK + ab_page&US", df2, return_type="dataframe")
vif = pd.DataFrame()
vif["feature"] = x.columns
vif["vif"] =  [variance_inflation_factor(x.values, i) for i in range(x.shape[1])]

vif
